{{Short description|Ancient type of Japanese bronze mirror}}
{{Italic title|reason=[[:category:kk]][[category:Japanese words and phrases]]}}
[[File:Bronze Mirror in Ancient Japan.jpg|thumb|''Sankakuen-shinjūkyō'' from the Tsubai Ōtsukayama kofun in [[Yamashiro, Kyoto]]]]
A {{nihongo|'''''Shinjū-kyō'''''|神獣鏡||"deity and beast mirror"}} is an ancient type of [[Japan]]ese round [[bronze mirror]] decorated with images of gods and animals from [[Chinese mythology]]. The obverse side has a polished mirror and the reverse has relief representations of legendary Chinese ''[[Shen (Chinese religion)|shén]]'' ({{lang|zh|神}} "spirit; god"), ''[[Xian (Taoism)|xiān]]'' ({{lang|zh|仙}} "transcendent; immortal"), and legendary creatures.

== History ==
The {{transl|ja|shinjū-kyō}} style of bronze mirror originated from the [[Chinese magic mirror|Chinese magic mirrors]] and was frequently produced during the [[Han dynasty]], [[Three Kingdoms]], and [[Six Dynasties]] (1st–6th centuries CE). With the spread of Chinese bronze casting technology, {{transl|ja|shinjūkyō}} were also produced in Japan and the [[Lelang Commandery]] and [[Daifang Commandery]] in the Korean peninsula. The {{circa|297}} {{transl|zh|Wei zhi}} ({{lang|zh|魏志}} "Records of Wei"), which is part of the ''[[Records of the Three Kingdoms]]'' ({{lang|zh|三國志}}), has the first historical reference to bronze mirrors in Japan. It chronicles tributary relations between Queen [[Himiko]] of [[Wa (Japan)|Wa]] and the Wei court, and records that in 239, Emperor [[Cao Rui]] sent presents to Himiko, including "one hundred bronze mirrors".{{sfnp|Goodrich|1951|p=15}}

== Variations ==
Archeological excavations of Japanese tombs from the [[Kofun period]] (3rd–7th centuries) have revealed numerous {{transl|ja|shinjūkyō}}, and Japanese archeologists divide them into subtypes including: 
*{{nihongo|''sankakuen-shinjūkyō''|三角縁神獣鏡||"triangular-rimmed deity and beast mirror"}}
*{{nihongo|''gamontai-shinjūkyō''|画文帯神獣鏡||"wide image-band deity and beast mirror"}} 
*{{nihongo|''hirabuchi-shinjūkyō''|平縁神獣鏡||"flat-rimmed deity and beast mirror"}} 
Kurotsuka ''[[kofun]]'' tomb excavated in [[Nara Prefecture]] contained 33 {{transl|ja|sankakuen-shinjūkyō}} bronze mirrors. Some scholars{{sfnp|Edwards|1998}}{{sfnp|Edwards|1999}}{{sfnp|Nishikawa|1999}} believe they are the original mirrors that Emperor Cao Rui presented to Queen Himiko, but others disagree.

